<br>
My system and set up is extremely wuss compared to most - it's a PIII-750 (slightly o/c'd) with an nVIDIA gf2 MX 400 and runs EQ at 1280x1024x16-bit color pretty decent - 1 GB of RAM probably helps, but that stuff is super cheap now, like 50-60 bucks and is probably one of the better comp investments you can make right now.  I have Level of Detail and Dynamic Lighting OFF, and use the texture cache - usually /part high and /showsp off but it depends.<br>
<br>
Doing the screenshots is as much art as science - it takes a fair amount of time, but I got a few tips from the pros that helped.<br>
<br>
Here's what I can pass on:<br>
<br>
Run at the highest resolution you find playable - when you resize a high resolution image down you'll have a much higher color density than if you're trying to blow up a low resolution picture and your image manipulation program will have far more data to play with in its compression cycle.<br>
<br>
As a follow on, crop your image before resizing if you're going smaller with the final, obviously.<br>
<br>
UV is a god send - while I actually prefer infra in-game (conditioning?), it simply makes for shitty ass screenshots due to being vertex lite red at night (thx Daelo).  So, acumen or the guise of the deceiver has become my perma buff (replacing Acid Jet or Rez Effects).<br>
<br>
This will vary with individual image manipulation programs, but with infra, you'll need to tone down the red - you'll also want to fiddle with the green.  Afterwards, you'll probably want to increase the contrast and brightness to bring out the actual substance of the picture.  This quickly becomes tedious and has never really produced good results - if you can get anything better than the tcar.jpg shot with infra, I'd appreciate it if you'd share.<br>
<br>
With UV, things are a little easier on the back end and the results are MUCH better - after you crop, adjust all levels, you will need to increase the curve on the low (dark) end up and left, and then play with the median and upper ends to bring out shadows and hints as necessary.  What makes brilliant pictures is then going to the contrast and brightness and adjusting them - typical values are 5 and 2 respectively, for me, but your application and taste may dictate otherwise.  VERY rarely, I will adjust the saturation if things come out flat - this is most pronounced when you have a really dark infra original, but trust me, don't use infra.<br>
<br>
Doing the chat box stuff is ALWAYS the most son of a bitch part, thank god for /wincolor chat.   It may be significantly faster to just retype them in your own image rather than cutting and pasting, but I am all anal about getting them out with no extra letter fragments, so take that for what you will.  A larger chat size would help, but I like having the small text to keep a lot of information immediately visible.<br>
<br>
I am not by any means an expert, but I do learn something each time and am consistently more pleased with my results - hope some of this info helps.<br>
<br>
-Tork<br>
